In traditional implementations, the cart would be stored directly in the database, often across multiple tables such as cart_items and menu_items, requiring joins every time a user retrieves or updates their cart. This approach quickly becomes a performance bottleneck, especially for high-traffic applications, because each cart read triggers multiple database queries and complex joins. In contrast, the current approach first queries the database only once to retrieve essential item details such as name and price—and then stores these details along with the menu_item_id and quantity in Redis, an in-memory store. This effectively applies intentional denormalization, duplicating some data outside its original table to optimize performance. Subsequent cart operations, including GET /cart, are served entirely from Redis, eliminating the need for repeated database queries and making cart retrieval extremely fast, even under heavy load. Additionally, this approach preserves a consistent user experience for example, if an admin changes the price of a menu item after a customer added it to their cart, the cart still shows the price the customer saw at the time of addition. Many large-scale e-commerce and high-traffic platforms adopt this pattern because it balances high performance, low database load, and reliable user experience, while keeping the database as the single source of truth for permanent data.


